annotations:
Roll up your sleeves
 And face the face it’s looking right back at me
 It’s easier to leave it oh
 It’s easier to fake it, oh oh

Rather than backing away from life’s challenges, it’s usually better to face them head on and “roll up our sleeves”. As Brené Brown points out, it’s natural to want to sidestep our discomfort. However, doing the exact opposite is what helps us truly rise above the pain. In this case, honesty seems to be the best policy!

annotations:
It’s all good, man up
 ’Cause I don’t say much when I don’t like it
Its about being in a situation where she looks back and wishes she had spoken up and stood up for herself.

You’re coming round too late
 I’ve taken off my face
 And you won’t like it

Australian Triple J radio presenter Gen Fricker stated she loved this as one of her favorite song beginnings when she first played Low Blows.

Here Mac is talking about about that her lover has come around later than she desired and she has already taken off her makeup (and maybe is also no longer dressed for visitors) and thinks she will be unattractive for them to see.

It’s also clear that Mac’s angry and frustrated as it starts with this complaint.
